                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/856b.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Extract.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-05T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 5, 1912—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your despatch No. 1618, of August 28. A note which treats fully of the three
                    points brought forward by the President in a conversation that he had with the
                    Mexican Ambassador yesterday is being forwarded to you to-day. If you deem some
                    alteration advisable in policy or otherwise you will telegraph your suggestions
                    and recommendations immediately. Otherwise you will at such early time as
                    appears to you most opportune officially present the note textually to the
                    Mexican Government, informing the Department by telegraph simultaneously of its
                    presentation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
